# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

1. Initialize `totalwater` to 0 and `n` to the length of the `height` array.

2. Create two arrays, `left` and `right`, to store the maximum heights on the left and right side of each building.

3. Calculate `left` and `right` arrays.

4. Iterate through each building and calculate the trapped water above it by comparing the minimum of the maximum heights on both sides with the building's height.

5. Accumulate the trapped water to get the total trapped water.

6. Return the total trapped water as the result.

This approach uses precomputed maximum heights on both sides of each building to determine how much rainwater can be trapped between them.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
     O(N)

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
    O(N)

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int trap(int[] height) {
        int totalwater=0;
        int n=height.length;
    int left[]=new int[n];
    int right[]=new int[n];

    left[0]=height[0];
    for(int i=1;i<=n-1;i++){
        left[i]=Math.max(left[i-1],height[i]);
    }
    right[n-1]=height[n-1];
    for(int i=n-2;i>=0;i--){
        right[i]=Math.max(right[i+1],height[i]);
    }

    for(int i=0;i<n-1;i++){
        int water=0;
        int ht=Math.min(left[i],right[i]);
        if(ht>=height[i]){
            water=ht-height[i];
            totalwater+=water;
        }


    }
    return totalwater;

    }
}
```

