# Intuition:

The problem requires us to find the node where the cycle begins in a linked list with a cycle. We can use the Floyd's cycle-finding algorithm to detect whether the linked list has a cycle or not, and also to determine the length of the cycle. Once we detect a cycle, we can use two pointers - one starting from the head of the linked list, and the other starting from the node where the cycle was detected. We then move both pointers one node at a time until they meet. The node where they meet is the node where the cycle begins.

# Approach:

Initialize two pointers - fast and slow - to the head of the linked list.
While fast and fast->next are not NULL, move slow one node at a time and fast two nodes at a time.
If fast and slow meet, it means there is a cycle in the linked list.
Once we detect a cycle, we reset slow to the head of the linked list, and keep fast where it is.
Move slow and fast one node at a time until they meet. The node where they meet is the node where the cycle begins.
If they never meet, it means there is no cycle in the linked list.
# Complexity:

- Time complexity: O(n) where n is the length of the linked list. We need to traverse the linked list once to detect the cycle, and then traverse it once more to find the node where the cycle begins.

- Space complexity: O(1). We only need to use two pointers to detect the cycle and find the node where it begins. No extra space is required.

