**Approach I - (hashing)**
i) Create a hashset to store nodes of the list.
ii) Iterare through list and check if node is present in list.
iii) If yes, loop detected and return that node.
iV) Else, insert that node in the set and move ahead.
v)  If iteration is completed, it means there is no cycle in the list. Retun null.

*T.C - O(n) & S.C - O(n)*
```
public ListNode detectCycle(ListNode head) {
        HashSet<ListNode> set = new HashSet<>();
        while(head!=null)
        {
            if(set.contains(head))
                return head;
            set.add(head);
            head = head.next;
        }
        return null;
    }
```
**Approach II - (two-pointer) Optimised**
i) Initially take two pointers, fast and slow. Fast pointer takes two steps ahead while slow pointer will take single          step ahead for each iteration.
ii) We know that if a cycle exists, fast and slow pointers will collide.
iii) If cycle does not exists, fast pointer will move to null.
iv) Else, when both slow and fast pointer collides, it detects a cycle exists.
v) Take another pointer, say entry. Point to the very first of the linked list.
vi) Move the slow and the entry pointer ahead by single steps until they collide. 
vii) Once they collide we get the starting node of the linked list.

*T.C- O(n) & S.C- O(1)*
```
public ListNode detectCycle(ListNode head) {
        ListNode slow = head, fast = head, entry = head;
        while(fast!=null && fast.next!=null)
        {
            slow = slow.next;
            fast = fast.next.next;
            if(slow==fast)
            {
                while(slow!=entry)
                {
                    slow = slow.next;
                    entry = entry.next;
                }
                return slow;
            }
        }
        return null;
    }
```

