# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
- This problem can be solved using **Floyd's cycle detection algorithm**, also known as the ***tortoise and hare*** algorithm.
- we will use `fastptr` and `slowptr`, to traversal and `fastptr` will move 2 step at a time  faster than `slowptr`.
- If there is a cycle in the linked list, the `fastptr` will eventually catch up to the `slowptr`
- Once they meet, we know that there is a cycle in the linked list.
- Now where they both meet, we then reset `slowptr` to head and again do the traversal but this time `both pointer at same speed` .
- Now when they will meet again that would be the `node` where the cycle begins
- Now return that node.
- If both pointer not meet for the first time then `fastptr` will reach null that means there is no loop in the linkedlist we will return `null` instead.



# Why Floyd's Cycle-Finding algorithm works ?
- There might me thought that why after first meeting resetting slowptr to head  and traversing at the same speed reaches to the cycle start.
- 
![IMG_20230309_140316 (1).jpg](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/8ca294fa-ecab-4e8c-9e2d-721867b1fdbb_1678351934.785868.jpeg)


- If there is confusion with `c3l` consider the case where cycle is smaller means z is smaller than x.
- then eventually before meeting one  pointer  will traverse some constant amount of cycle `c3l +z` to meet at cycle starting point  


# Code
```
/**
 * Definition for singly-linked list.
 * class ListNode {
 *     int val;
 *     ListNode next;
 *     ListNode(int x) {
 *         val = x;
 *         next = null;
 *     }
 * }
 */
public class Solution {
    public ListNode detectCycle(ListNode head) {

      ListNode fptr = head;
      ListNode sptr = head;

    //Move the slow pointer one step and the fast pointer two steps at a time 
    //through the linked list,
    // until they either meet or the fast pointer reaches the end of the list.
      while(fptr != null && fptr.next!= null){
        fptr = fptr.next.next;
        sptr = sptr.next;
        // If the pointers meet, there is a cycle in the linked list.
        // Reset the slow pointer to the head of the linked list, and now move both  
        // pointers one step at a time at same speed,
        // until they meet again. The node where they meet is the starting point of
        // the cycle.
        if(fptr==sptr){
          sptr = head;

          while(sptr!=fptr){
            fptr= fptr.next;
            sptr= sptr.next;
          }
          return sptr;
        }
      }
    // If the fast pointer reaches the end of the list without meeting the slow 
    //pointer,
    // there is no cycle in the linked list. Return null.
      return null;

    }
}
```

