# Intuition
We will use fast slow pointer approach
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach
The following steps are required:

1. Initially take two pointers, fast and slow. The fast pointer takes two steps ahead while the slow pointer will take a single step ahead for each iteration.
2. We know that if a cycle exists, fast and slow pointers will collide.
3. If the cycle does not exist, the fast pointer will move to NULL
Else, when both slow and fast pointer collides, it detects a cycle exists.
4. Take another pointer, say entry. Point to the very first of the linked list.
5. Move the slow and the entry pointer ahead by single steps until they collide. 
6. Once they collide we get the starting node of the linked list.

![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/60be8298-b04e-494d-931d-bc705b175570_1683405503.2431746.png)

![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/88bc5689-6bc4-44e1-b592-0f46c801aa93_1683405527.745601.png)

We can see that the fast and slow pointer collides which shows the cycle exists. The entry pointer is pointed to the head of the list. And move them forward until it collides with the slow pointer

![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/723c616e-ef03-43f5-bce9-ac171af288be_1683405568.3892686.png)



<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- Time complexity:O(N)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:O(1)
