solutions.content:
**Algorithm explain**

There are two pointers p_slow, p_fast start from head, and the speed of p_fast is two times of p_slow. (Floyd's algorithm)
First, we need to anaylze two kinds of scenario:
1. p_slow meet p_fast at middle of the loop 
<img src="https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/2fe20af9-0c00-422c-b203-062e8db7301a_1614574604.2953987.png" alt="closed_paren" width="300" height="200"/>
2. p_slow meet p_fast at the ans point
<img src="https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/55a3d298-2b8f-463d-a956-ea21ea44ef88_1614579587.3817356.png" alt="closed_paren" width="300" height="200"/>

Assume: 1. Distance from head to ans is **a**; 2. ans to meet is **b**; meet to ans is **c**
Some explaination say a = c but **a is not always equal to c!**

-----

**In the first scenario**

The distance of p_slow (***Ds***) is ***a+b***
The distance of p_fast (***Df***) is ***a+n(b+c)+b***, where n is the possible times p_fast runs in the loop.
Due to the speed of p_fast is two times of p_slow, ***Df = 2Ds*** 
Therefore, ***a+n(b+c)+b = 2a+2b*** => ***a = n(b+c)-b***

For example, if we have a list that has 9 nodes, and the 9th node links to 6th node.
O-O-O-O-O-O-O-O-O
We can fine the meet node is 5th node, and now a = 5, b = 3, c = 1, n = 2

------

**In the second scenario**

The distance of p_fast (***Df***) is ***a***. It is not possible that p_slow needs to run through the loop to meet p_fast at the start of the loop.
The distance of p_slow (***Ds***) is ***a+n(b)***
Due to the speed of p_fast is two times of p_slow, ***Df = 2Ds*** 
Therefore, ***a+n(b) = 2a*** => ***a = n(b)***

For example, if we have a list that has 10 nodes, and the 10th node links to 9th node.
O-O-O-O-O-O-O-O-O-O
We can fine the meet node is 9th node, and now a = 8, b = 2, n = 4

-----

**Analysis of two scenrio's equation**

***a = n(b+c)-b*** 
If you are lucky, your pointer on p_fast only need to loop once to find the meet node. The value of a is equal to c. If p_fast has to loop over more than one times, a is not equal to c anymore. However, the equation will still make sure two new pointers that you put on head node and meet node will meet at answer node. e.g. (n=2) a = b+2c, b+c is the full loop, and the extra c will help you go to the ans node.  (n=3) a = 2b+3c, 2b+2c is the full loop, and the extra c helps you again.......so on and so forth.

***a = n(b)***
In this scenario, the full loop is b, so n(b) ensure the our meet pointer will run full loop to meet head pointer at ans node.

-----

**Summary**

So in any scenario, putting one pointer on head node and one pointer on meet node and move them by single step will ensure they meet at the answer node. 

If you like my explaination, you can give me a upvote, thanks.

-----

```
/* Concept: Use Floyd's loop dection to find the meet node,
 *          then use two pointers one on node and one on meet node,
 *          steps by steps, the point they meet is the cycle begin
 */
struct ListNode *detectCycle(struct ListNode *head) {
    struct ListNode *p_slow = head;
    struct ListNode *p_fast = head;
    struct ListNode *p_meet;
    int loop_flag = false;

    while ((p_slow != NULL) && (p_fast != NULL) && ((p_fast->next) != NULL)) {
        p_slow = p_slow->next;
        p_fast = p_fast->next->next;

        if (p_slow == p_fast) {
            p_meet = p_slow;
            loop_flag = true;
            break;
        }
    }


    if (loop_flag == false) {
        return NULL;
    }
    else {
        p_slow = head;
        while (p_slow != p_meet) {
            p_slow = p_slow->next;
            p_meet = p_meet->next;
        }
    }
    return p_slow;
}
```

