# Approach
- It takes a singly-linked list represented as a pointer to the head node as input. The goal of this function is to detect if there's a cycle in the linked list and return the node where the cycle begins, or NULL if there is no cycle.

- Here's the approach used in this code:

- Initialize two pointers, slow and fast, both initially pointing to the head of the linked list. The slow pointer advances one node at a time, while the fast pointer advances two nodes at a time.

- Use a while loop to traverse the linked list with the fast and slow pointers. If there is no cycle in the linked list, the fast pointer will eventually reach the end of the list, and the loop will terminate. However, if there is a cycle, the fast pointer will eventually catch up to the slow pointer, and they will meet at some point within the cycle. This is checked using the condition if (slow == fast).

- If a cycle is detected (i.e., the slow and fast pointers meet), set a boolean variable cycle to true to indicate that a cycle exists.

- After detecting the cycle, reset the fast pointer to the head of the linked list and keep the slow pointer where it is.

- Use another while loop to traverse the linked list again with both the fast and slow pointers, but this time at the same speed (both advance one node at a time). When they meet again, it will be at the node where the cycle begins.

- Finally, return the fast pointer, which now points to the start of the cycle, or NULL if no cycle was found.

- This code leverages the Floyd's Tortoise and Hare (Cycle Detection) algorithm to efficiently detect cycles in a singly-linked list
