##### **Step 1) Hare-Tortoise Algorithm/Floyds cycle finding algorithm**
1. Create two pointers fast and slow, move the two pointers through the sequence at different speed.
1. Move the fast pointer at twice the speed.
1. While traversing the linked list one of these things will occur-
	* The Fast pointer may reach the end (NULL) this shows that there is no loop in the linked list.
	* The Fast pointer again catches the slow pointer at some time therefore a loop exists in the linked list.
1. If fast is equal to slow hence loop exist else return NULL.

##### **Step 2) Finding loops Head if it Exists-**
IF loop exist- Let us assume that the distance from start to where the loop start is *x1*, total distance traversed by slow be *(x1+x2)* (Where x2 is the distance from loop start to current position of slow pointer)  & total distance traversed by fast be *(x1+x2+x3+x2)* (where x3 is the distance which is starting from slow pointer's current position till the loop reaches its start).
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/6a079946-bc53-4a52-a8bc-da78d4c42117_1661018193.2814949.jpeg)
As we can observe total length of loop is (length travelled by fast)-(length travelled by slow), total Length of loop is x3+x2 which could be seen evidently from above.
Hence, x3+x2=(x1+x2+x3+x2)-(x1+x2)
On calculating from above eq->**x3=x1**

* As now when fast and slow are equal we equate slow to head and start moving the pointers to next position again.
* Fast will reach loop start after travelling a distance of x3 and the slow pointer which is now pointing to head will travel x1 distance before reaching loop start, as x3=x1 so they will reach the loop start together, hence we can return the loop start by returning fast or slow now.

