# Intuition

Let's have two pointers, slow and fast. After each iteration, slow moves one step ahead, while fast moves two steps ahead. Let's call the point where they meet, `meeting point`. If they never meet, the list doesn't have a cycle and we can return nil.

If they do meet, the distance to the start of the cycle from both the meeting point and head will be exactly same, proof in the attached image below.

![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/e3ae581f-b0e4-4a9d-a669-d5857717ff78_1673181439.7291806.png)


# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$

- Space complexity: $$O(1)$$

# Code
```
func detectCycle(head *ListNode) *ListNode {
    var slow *ListNode = head
    var fast *ListNode = head
    cycleFound := false

    // let's find the meeting point first
    for fast != nil && fast.Next != nil {
        slow = slow.Next
        fast = fast.Next.Next
        if slow == fast {
            cycleFound = true
            break
        }
    }

    if !cycleFound { return nil }

    // the distance to cycle start from both the 
    // head and meeting point are same
    for slow != head {
        head = head.Next
        slow = slow.Next
    }
    return head
}
```

