solutions.content:
Let's assume the cycle starts at the **yth** node,
and two pointers *fast*(travel 2 steps at a time) and *slow*(one step at a time) meet at the **xth** node.(note that *slow* can't have traversed the whole list when chased by *fast*),
and we let the cycle length be **m**.

We know that *fast* has travelled **2x** nodes when it meets *slow*,
and when they meet, *fast* has first reached **yth** node, then travelled through the cycle for **k** times(**k** is an integer >=0 ), and at last take another **x-y** steps beyond the cycle starting node( **yth** node ) to meet *slow*.
So **2x**=**y**+**km**+(**x**-**y**)    ==>    **x**=**km**.

Then we set another *seek* pointer which also travels 1 step a time to meet *slow*.
When *seek* reached **yth** node, *slow* has totally travelled through **x**+**y** nodes.
Because **x**=**km**, we have **x**+**y**=**y**+**km**.
Hence when *seek* is at **yth** node, *slow* has taken **y**+**km** steps, and cuz **m** is cycle length,
*slow* must also have travelled back to the **yth** node.

That's when *slow* and *seek* first meet, at the **yth** node, which is the start of the cycle!

