solutions.content:
Main ideas:

1. Detect whether or not there is a cycle by using the typical algorithm with a slow and a fast pointer.
2. Once the slow and the fast pointers meet, find the length of the cycle. Let that length be X.
3. Start again from the head of the list and initialize two pointers, call them p1 and p2 (you can reuse the slow and fast pointers if you want). Let p2 travel X steps ahead. Then run a while loop where you move both p1 and p2 until they meet.

In step 3, since the distance between p1 and p2 is X, you know that when they meet, they will meet at the entrance of the cycle. 

```
ListNode *detectCycle(ListNode *head) {
        if(head == NULL) return NULL;
        ListNode* slow, * fast;
        slow = head;
        fast = head;
        bool found = false;
        while(fast->next!=NULL && fast->next->next!=NULL){
            slow = slow->next;
            fast = fast->next->next;
            if(slow == fast){
                found = true;
                break;
            }
        }
        if(!found) return NULL;

        int len = 1;
        ListNode * cur = slow;
        while(cur->next!=slow){
            len++;
            cur = cur->next;
        }

        int i = 0;
        slow = head;
        fast = head;
        for(i = 0;i<len;i++){
            fast = fast->next;
        }
        while(slow!=fast){
            slow = slow->next;
            fast = fast->next;
        }

        return slow;
    }
```

